  "summary": "U.S. stocks sold off sharply on Thursday as escalating Iran conflict rocked energy markets, with WTI crude surging over 8% past $81 a barrel after Iran claimed it struck an oil tanker in the Persian Gulf. The Dow plunged 785 points (-1.6%) to 47,955 while the S&P 500 fell 0.6% to 6,831, erasing year-to-date gains and failing to breach 6,900 resistance. Airlines led the decline with United and Delta both down over 5%, while Broadcom bucked the trend rising 4.8% on strong earnings and The Trade Desk surged 19% on reported OpenAI ad partnership talks. China set its 2026 GDP target at 4.5-5%, the lowest in decades, and markets now await tomorrow's February nonfarm payrolls report.",
